## 3. Regressor — parallel heads + refinement pass

> **IMPORTANT — read first: decoder vs. scalar regressor are two different models.**
> The parallel-heads / cascade / refinement discussion below was about predicting
> **k global scalars** (one number per filter for the whole image). The **decoder**
> (Section 1) predicts a **256×256×k coefficient map** instead — k spatial maps, not
> k scalars. **If you commit to the decoder, the entire `CascadeArgumentRegressor`
> goes away and is replaced by the decoder + a coefficient head.** Don't build both
> a scalar regressor and a decoder in the same model — pick one. The scalar variant
> below is only worth keeping as a **separate ablation** (global vs spatial).
>
> **"Should the decoder use parallel heads?"** — slightly mismatched question. The
> decoder has no scalar "heads"; the k per-filter outputs are just channels of the
> decoder's final conv. The real decision is *how the k coefficient channels are
> produced and whether they interact*:
>
> - **Option A — single conv head (start here).** Decoder → one `Conv(C → k)` → k
>   coefficient maps. The spatial analog of "parallel": all k produced together from
>   shared features, no explicit interaction (they interact implicitly via shared
>   decoder features). Cheapest, correct first baseline. At pixel level there's far
>   more capacity than the 9-scalar bottleneck, so the overshoot problem is **less
>   severe** here — test A before adding machinery.
> - **Option B — per-filter conv branches.** Literal spatial parallel heads, one
>   branch per filter. Usually **skip it** — adds params and lets filters overshoot
>   (they don't see each other), same flaw as scalar parallel heads.
> - **Option C — single head + channel-mixing refinement (spatial analog of the
>   scalar "parallel + refinement").** Decoder → `Conv(C → k)` initial maps → small
>   refinement block (a couple convs over the k coefficient channels + decoder
>   features) → k *corrected* maps. Add this **only if Option A shows filters
>   fighting** (over-bright / over-saturated regions). Symmetric, no order bias.
>
> Bottom line for the decoder: **A first, add C if you see overshoot.** Section 3
> below applies only to a kept scalar-variant ablation.

### Background (why we're here)
- **Cascade regressor (paper, Eq. 7):** predicts filter args sequentially, each
  conditioned on the previous. Models filter interactions (brightness/highlight both
  push bright pixels) — paper ablation MSE 28.47 → 26.85. But it was **order-sensitive
  and over-weighted the first and last heads** (gradient/length imbalance in a chain).
- **Pure parallel heads:** fixed the first/last bias, but reintroduced the problem the
  cascade solved — filters predicted in isolation **accumulate and overshoot**. This is
  the paper's *worse* baseline (~28.47). Worse with the new color filters, which
  interact heavily.
- **Self-attention over filter tokens:** trained but **worse MSE**. At k≈9 tokens
  attention is data-hungry and under-supervised; tokens all seeded from the same pooled
  vector → weak keys/values → tends to collapse. Attention shines at dozens–hundreds of
  tokens, not ~9.

### The chosen approach: parallel heads → refinement
Permutation-symmetric (no first/last bias — fixes the original complaint) **and** models
decision-level interaction (what the cascade gave you):

1. **Parallel heads** produce initial arguments `a_1…a_k` independently from the
   pooled/global feature. No order bias.
2. **Form tokens** that include the *predicted argument values* `a_i` (not just
   features) — this is the key: later correction sees each filter's actual decision.
3. **1–2 refinement rounds** (small attention+MLP, or just a symmetric MLP mixer) take
   all k predictions together and output **corrected** arguments. Filters de-conflict
   symmetrically.

### Make the refinement trainable (this is where attention failed before)
- **Pre-LayerNorm + residual** around the refinement block. Without these a tiny
  attention/MLP on a regression target often won't beat the mean.
- **1–2 heads max**, correct `1/√d` scaling, **stack 2 small layers** not 1 (single
  layer underfits the interaction).
- **Give tokens distinct content:** seed each from a per-filter linear projection of the
  feature **+** its learned embedding **+** its initial predicted argument — not the same
  pooled vector for all.

### Cheaper fallback if attention still struggles at k≈9
**Symmetric MLP mixer:** concatenate all k initial predictions + the shared feature →
one shared MLP → k corrections. No attention machinery, far easier to train at this
token count, often **matches** attention when k is small. Treat MLP-mixer and
attention-refinement as the two real contenders; run both as ablations.

### Also check (likely root cause of the original cascade bias)
The paper's **dynamic loss strategy (Eq. 12)** exists precisely to stop the regressor
biasing toward particular filters. The first/last over-weighting you saw is the symptom
it targets — **confirm dynamic loss is actually on and working**. A disabled/broken
dynamic loss reproduces exactly that bias regardless of regressor design.

---

## Suggested ordering across all three

1. Lock the **decoder** with **Option A (single conv head)** — coefficient-resolution
   sweep + TV loss + filter audit + synthetic-supervision fix. This is the change with
   a real shot at 40 PSNR. (The decoder **replaces** the scalar regressor — not both.)
2. If Option A shows filters overshooting, add **Option C (channel-mixing refinement)**
   over the k coefficient maps. Optionally keep a **scalar variant (Section 3) as a
   separate global-vs-spatial ablation** — but that's a different model.
3. Swap **B0 → B3 / ConvNeXt-Tiny** last, to feed the spatial head better; measure delta.
4. Throughout: log **PSNR + peak memory across resolutions vs HDNet** — the contribution
   is *quality parity at any resolution with far less memory*, so that table is the paper.
